# PBRD Lite + Full PBRD

Before coding, classify the task:

- **SMALL**: 1-3 files; no auth, Stripe, billing, subscription gating, Firestore rules/schema, customer data, migrations, deployment, data deletion, customer data exposure risk, tenant isolation risk, permission/role changes, or security-sensitive logic. Use PBRD Lite: minimal file reads, last 40 lines of `agent-info.md` only if needed, keyword-search lessons if needed, 1-3 bullet mini plan, smallest change, review changed files only, no Document agent unless user-facing behavior changed.
- **MEDIUM**: 4-8 files, workflow or user-facing change, but no high-risk systems. Use normal Plan + Build + Review with focused context. Read recent memory entries only, relevant lessons only, and run Document only if user-facing behavior, setup instructions, app workflow, or feature descriptions changed.
- **LARGE**: Always Full PBRD for auth, Stripe, billing, subscription gating, Firestore rules/schema, customer data, customer data exposure risk, tenant isolation risk, permission/role changes, migrations, data deletion, production deployment, replacement workflow, monthly workspace source-of-truth logic, major reporting, security-sensitive logic, or more than 8 files.

Token budget rules:

- Do not read full large files or full `agent-info.md` by default; prefer the last 40 lines or targeted ranges.
- Search `lessons_learned.md` / `lessons-learned.md` for relevant keywords before reading broad sections.
- Do not rewrite `agent-system/plan.md` for SMALL tasks.
- Do not run all agents for SMALL tasks.
- Keep plans, reviews, memory entries, and final responses concise.
- Avoid repeating project context already stored in workflow docs or memory.

Document Agent runs only when a feature changed, setup/deployment/env/pricing/data model/docs became inaccurate, app workflow changed, or user-facing behavior changed. Do not run it for tiny bug fixes, styling-only changes, typo fixes, logs, test-only changes, comments-only changes, or internal refactors with no behavior change.

Never skip review for LARGE/high-risk work. Review must explicitly check SaaS security risks when applicable: customer data exposure, tenant isolation, org-scoped queries, role/permission enforcement, client trust boundaries, Firestore/Storage rules, Stripe billing source-of-truth boundaries, deletion/export/report/log PII leakage, and overpromised compliance/privacy/security copy.
